TY  - JOUR
T1  - Portfolio Choices in the Presence of Other Risks
AU  - Finkelshtain, Israel
AU  - Chalfant, James A.
Y1  - 1993/08/01
PY  - 1993
DA  - 1993/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.39.8.925
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.39.8.925
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 925
EP  - 936
VL  - 39
IS  - 8
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - The effects of multivariate risk are examined in a model of portfolio choice. The conditions under which portfolio choices are separable from consumption decisions are derived. Unless the appropriate restrictions hold on investors' preferences or on the probability distribution of risks, the optimal portfolio is affected by other risks. This requires generalizing the usual measures of risk aversion. With one risky asset, matrix measures of risk aversion are used to generalize the results of Arrow (1965) and Pratt (1964) concerning the effects of risk aversion and wealth on the optimal portfolio. With two risky assets, the choices made by two investors coincide if and only if their generalized risk-aversion measures are identical. Ross's notion of stronger risk aversion is then used to characterize the effect of risk aversion on the level of investment in the riskier asset.
AB  - The effects of multivariate risk are examined in a model of portfolio choice. The conditions under which portfolio choices are separable from consumption decisions are derived. Unless the appropriate restrictions hold on investors' preferences or on the probability distribution of risks, the optimal portfolio is affected by other risks. This requires generalizing the usual measures of risk aversion. With one risky asset, matrix measures of risk aversion are used to generalize the results of Arrow (1965) and Pratt (1964) concerning the effects of risk aversion and wealth on the optimal portfolio. With two risky assets, the choices made by two investors coincide if and only if their generalized risk-aversion measures are identical. Ross's notion of stronger risk aversion is then used to characterize the effect of risk aversion on the level of investment in the riskier asset.
